Thank you very much. I heard Sahai is a nightmare to many students. I also do not have a good background in circuits. What do you think I should do to prepare for the EE16B class? I tried to use the class website but it seems that all the hw solutions are hidden from students/viewers. Thanks.
If you want a lighter class, take it a semester Sahai's not teaching it. He isn't teaching it Spring 2020 afaik. But if you care about learning EE/math, then challenge yourself with Sahai.

EE16B isn't only about circuits or physics, you're exposed to a lot of really cool math from principal component analysis to discrete Fourier transforms. I don't know if declared cs transfer students get any reserved seats for ee16b, but I would advise against postponing the 16 series. They're incredibly helpful in building the mathematical foundations for other courses like cs189.
